{"title_page": "Neverland Ranch", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Personal home of Michael Jackson}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Neverland Valley Ranch \n| image = NeverlandRides.jpg\n| caption = Neverland Ranch amusement rides pictured in August 2008\n| location = 5225 Figueroa Mountain Road, [[Los Olivos, California|Los Olivos]]\n| location2 = [[California]]\n| location3 = United States\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.74107|-120.09158|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-CA|display=title,inline}}\n| status = closed\n| owner = Estate of [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Colony Capital]]\n| area = {{convert|2700|acre}}\n| homepage = www.sycamorevalley.com\n}}\n\n[[File:Neverland Ranch's gates.jpg|thumb|right|Neverland Ranch gates]]\n'''Sycamore Valley Ranch'''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Characterization of pathway engineered strains of filamentous fungi in submerged cultures|last=Poulsen, B. R.|isbn=9085041546|oclc=1016620715}}</ref>  (formerly and most famously '''Neverland Ranch''',<ref name=\"NNM\">[http://www.edhat.com/site/tidbit.cfm?id=2752 \"Neverland Never More\"], by William Etling (author of ''Sideways in Neverland: Life in the Santa Ynez Valley''), EdHat.com, 2009.</ref> or simply '''Neverland''') is a developed property in [[Santa Barbara County, California]], located at 5225 Figueroa Mountain Road, [[Los Olivos, California]], on the edge of [[Los Padres National Forest]]. It is known for being the home and private [[amusement park]] of American entertainer [[Michael Jackson]] from 1988 until 2005.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6128664/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-frozen-in-time|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Frozen in Time|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2014-06-20|accessdate=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref name=\"Petersen\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Ellis-Petersen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/aug/01/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-sell-50-million|title=Michael Jackson Neverland Ranch expected to fetch up to $85m|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=2014-08-01|accessdate=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sophie Smith|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/abroad/michael-jacksonsneverland-ranch-returns-market-amid-documentary/|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch returns to the market amid documentary controversy|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=March 4, 2019|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOriginally named '''Zaca Laderas Ranch''', the estate was renamed to Sycamore Valley Ranch shortly after it was purchased by property developer William Bone in 1981.<ref name=\"Time\"/> In 1988, the ranch was sold to Jackson, who renamed it after [[Neverland]], the fantasy island in the story of [[Peter Pan]], a boy who never grows up.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"Petersen\"/> Jackson's first encounter with the ranch came when he visited [[Paul McCartney]], who was staying there during their filming of the \"[[Say Say Say]]\" video in 1983. According to [[La Toya Jackson]], Michael expressed interest to her in someday owning the property at that time.<ref>{{cite book|author1=La Toya Jackson|author2=Jeffr\u00e9 Phillips|title=Starting Over|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SeQfvRHvZfwC&pg=PA69|year=2012|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2059-7|page=69}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, the ranch is owned by [[Colony Capital]] and has been for sale for several years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erincarlyle/2015/05/29/sale-of-michael-jacksons-100-million-neverland-ranch-would-be-win-for-colony-capital/#75f257361c8a|title=Sale Of Michael Jackson's $100 Million Neverland Ranch Would Be Win For Colony Capital|last=Carlyle |first=Erin|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> The ranch is located about 5 miles (8&nbsp;km) north of unincorporated Los Olivos, and about eight miles (13&nbsp;km) north of the town of [[Santa Ynez, California|Santa Ynez]]. The Chamberlin Ranch is to the west, and the rugged La Laguna Ranch, is to the north. The Santa Barbara County Assessor's office says the ranch is approximately 2,700 acres (1100 hectares).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4792028.stm | title=Dispute shuts down Jackson ranch | work=[[BBC News]] | date=2006-03-10 | accessdate=2007-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nThe estate was originally known as the '''Zaca Laderas Ranch''' at the time of its purchase by the property developer William Bone in 1981.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Bone renamed the estate the '''Sycamore Valley Ranch''' and moved there with his family. Bone commissioned the architect Robert Altevers to design the principal buildings on the ranch, and the pair spent two and a half years researching potential designs and ideas. The 13,000 square foot (1,200 m\u00b2) main house was completed in 1982, based on a design by Altevers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/01/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-relisted--with-a-big-price-cut.html|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch relisted \u2013 with a big price cut|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> with formal gardens, a stone bridge, and a four-acre lake with a five-foot waterfall. Bone later said that in building the house he had \"...a desire to express everything I had learned in 15 years of home building...I achieved here all the things I wanted to do in my business but could not\".<ref name=AD09>{{cite news|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/neverland-ranch-article|title=Neverland|date=October 31, 2009|work=[[Architectural Digest]]|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> He had considered converting the property to a country club but did not do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/la-me-jacksontimeline-neverland-story.html|title=Hot Property: Michael Jackson to Be Home on the Range|last=Ryon|first=Ruth|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n\n==Residence of Michael Jackson==\n[[File:Aerial-NeverlandTrainStation.jpg|thumb|Neverland's train station, Katherine Station, with [[floral clock]]<ref>https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/neverland-ranch-michael-jackson-article</ref>]]\n\nJackson purchased the estate from Bone in 1988<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news |title=At Neverland, they believe |work=USA Today |first=Cesar G |last=Soriano |date=2003-11-24 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/2003-11-23-neverland-believe_x.htm }}</ref> for an unknown amount: some sources indicate $19.5 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-for-sale-20150528-story.html|title=Neverland Ranch, former home of Michael Jackson, on the market for $100M|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/troymcmullen/2017/03/01/a-33-million-price-cut-for-michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch/#141c22ba18e6|title=A $33 Million Price Cut for Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch|last=McMullen|first=Troy|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> while others suggest it was closer to $30 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1988-03-20/realestate/re-1930_1_michael-jackson|title=Michael Jackson to Be Home on the Range|last=Ryon|first=Ruth|date=1988-03-20|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Vegas Hosting Big Jackson Family Auction. |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Fox News |date=2007-05-29 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,276076,00.html?sPage=fnc/entertainment/jackson |access-date=2019-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524084833/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,276076,00.html?sPage=fnc%2Fentertainment%2Fjackson |archive-date=2013-05-24 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The property was initially purchased by a [[Trust law|trust]] with Jackson's lawyer, John Branca, and his accountant, Marshall Gelfand, as trustees, for reasons of privacy. The arrangement was later rescinded by Jackson in April 1988 and he became the ultimate owner of the property.<ref name=\"Taraborrelli2010\">{{cite book|author=J. Randy Taraborrelli|title=Michael Jackson: The Magic, the Madness, the Whole Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=99AABNGOHGYC|year=2010|publisher=Pan|isbn=978-0-330-51565-8|page=386}}</ref> It was Jackson's home as well as his private amusement park, with numerous artistic garden statues and a [[petting zoo]].\n\nThe property included three railroads: one {{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]] named \"Neverland Valley Railroad\", with a steam locomotive named ''Katherine'' after his mother ([[Crown Metal Products|Crown]] {{whyte|4-4-0}} (2B), built in 1973), and two coaches. The other was a {{RailGauge|2ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]], with a  [[C. P. Huntington#Working replicas|C. P. Huntington replica locomotive]] made by [[Chance Rides]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steamlocomotive.com/lists/searchdb.php?str=Neverland+Ranch&country=USA|title=Surviving Steam Locomotive Search|work=steamlocomotive.com}}</ref> There was also a custom-made private electric train that was purchased by Jackson for his own children Prince, Paris and Blanket. The train was manufactured in 2001 from a German company [https://www.merkur-kids.de/ Elektro-Mobiltechnik]. The train was set up in the yard at Neverland behind the main house and had 100 feet of track.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-02/michael-jackson-s-neverland-ranch-train-is-coming-to-auction|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Train Is Coming to Auction|date=2019-06-07|access-date=2019-06-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThere was also a [[Ferris wheel]], [[Carousel]], [[Zipper (ride)|Zipper]], [[Octopus (ride)|Octopus]], [[Pirate ship (ride)|Pirate Ship]], [[Wave Swinger]], Super Slide, [[roller coaster]], [[bumper car]]s, and an [[amusement arcade]]. The master closet also contained a secret [[safe room]] for security.\n\nSome of the events that took place at the Ranch included the wedding of [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Larry Fortensky]] in 1991, the live [[Oprah Winfrey]] interview of Jackson in 1993, and an event in 1995 when Jackson and [[Lisa Marie Presley]] hosted children from around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2014/06/22/michael_jacksons_neverland_remains_in_limbo_years_after_his_death.html|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland remains in limbo years after his death {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNeverland Ranch was searched extensively by police officers in connection with the ''[[Trial of Michael Jackson|People v. Jackson]]'' trial after he was charged with multiple counts of [[Sexual abuse|molesting]] a minor in 2003. Jackson was acquitted of all charges. However, Jackson stated he would never live at the property again as he no longer considered the ranch a home and did not return to Neverland.<ref name=\"rollingstone1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-selling-for-67-million-w469968|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Devalued in Real Estate Market|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> Jackson's sister, [[La Toya Jackson|La Toya]], wrote of her experience staying at the ranch during her brother's trial in her 2012 memoir ''Starting Over''.<ref name=\"JacksonPhillips2012\">{{cite book|author1=La Toya Jackson|author2=Jeffr\u00e9 Phillips|title=Starting Over|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SeQfvRHvZfwC|date=29 May 2012|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2059-7|page=297}}</ref> In 2006, the facilities were closed and most of the staff were dismissed, with a spokesperson stating that this was the reflection of the fact that Jackson no longer lived there.\n\nNeverland Ranch has a central role in the allegations against Jackson of [[child sexual abuse]]; it is one of the main sites where Jackson's accusers have said the sexual abuse took place. The ranch's association with sexual abuse allegations was described as a possible reason for a significant decrease in value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/feb/28/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-reduces-price-by-70m|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch cuts sale price by $69m|first=Guardian|last=music|date=28 February 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/neverland-ranch-for-sale-michael-jackson.html</ref>\n\n==Financial status==\nReports of foreclosure proceedings against Neverland Ranch were published on October 22, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tmz.com/2007/11/06/neverland-in-foreclosure/ |date=2007-11-06 |accessdate=2007-11-07 |title=Neverland in Foreclosure? |publisher=TMZ.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ml-implode.com/info/jackson-NOD.pdf |title=Foreclosure Detail Report |accessdate=2007-11-07}}</ref> A spokesperson for Jackson said that the loan was merely being [[refinancing|refinanced]] and Jackson (later his estate) remained the majority stake holder, with a legal retention of 87.5% of the ranch.<ref name=\"scribd.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/101284813/mj-estate-second-accounting|title=MJ Estate Second Accounting|work=scribd.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7088491.stm|date=2007-11-10|accessdate=2007-11-10|title=Jackson 'will not lose Neverland'|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aerial-NeverlandZoo.jpg|thumb|Former zoo buildings, July 2009]]\nOn February 25, 2008, Jackson received word from Financial Title Company, the trustee, that unless he paid off $24,525,906.61 by March 19, a [[public auction]] would go forward of the land, buildings, and other items such as the rides, trains, and art.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/projects/pdf/AR-BC320_20080226_114706.pdf Notice of Trustee's Sale], Santa Barbara County Recorder via Fox News [http://www.sbcvote.com/opis/details.aspx?DocNum=2008-0010131 Record no. 2008-0010131]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, February 25, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Neverland Ranch Set for Auction |agency=Associated Press |work=Forbes |date=2008-02-26 |url=https://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2008/02/26/ap4700673.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080317164555/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2008/02/26/ap4700673.html |archivedate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref> On March 13, 2008, Jackson's lawyer L. Londell McMillan announced that a private agreement had been reached with the private investment group, [[Fortress Investment Group|Fortress Investment]], to save Jackson's ownership of the ranch.<ref name=saves>{{cite news |title=Michael Jackson 'saves Neverland' |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7295101.stm |date=2008-03-13 |accessdate=2008-03-13 }}</ref> Before the agreement, Jackson owed three months' [[arrears]] on the property.<ref name=saves/> McMillan did not reveal the details of the deal.\n\nOn May 12, 2008, a [[foreclosure]] [[auction]] for the ranch was canceled after [[Colony Capital]], an investment company run by billionaire Tom Barrack, purchased the [[loan]], which was in default. The selling price was $22.5 million.<ref name=\"rollingstone1\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Foreclosure auction on Jackson's Neverland Ranch is canceled |agency=Associated Press |publisher=CNN |date=2008-05-13 |accessdate=2008-05-13 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/12/jackson.neverland.ap/index.html |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080514020618/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/12/jackson.neverland.ap/index.html |archivedate = May 14, 2008}}</ref> In a press release, Jackson stated, \"I am pleased with recent developments involving Neverland Ranch and I am in discussions with Colony and [[Tom Barrack]] with regard to the Ranch and other matters that would allow me to focus on the future.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Neverland Ranch Note Sold to Colony Capital |publisher=Business Wire |date=2008-05-11 |accessdate=2008-05-13 |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080511005036/en }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5hZNgbrgnco68wdSY5q0bFdgp2MYgD90KF3F80 |title=Neverland Ranch foreclosure auction canceled |agency=Associated Press |date=2008-05-12 |accessdate=2008-05-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518174244/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5hZNgbrgnco68wdSY5q0bFdgp2MYgD90KF3F80 |archivedate=May 18, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 10, 2008, Jackson transferred the title to Sycamore Valley Ranch Company, LLC, and neighbors reported immediate activity on the property, including the amusement rides being trucked along the highway.<ref name=NNM/> Jackson still owned an unknown stake in the property, since Sycamore Valley Ranch was a [[joint venture]] between Jackson (represented by McMillan) and an affiliate of Colony Capital.<ref>[http://www.taletela.com/news/775/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-is-sold Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Is Sold] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727103118/http://www.taletela.com/news/775/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-is-sold |date=2009-07-27 }}. TaleTela. Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref><ref>[https://www.tmz.com/2008/11/12/neverland-may-be-jackos-ticket-to-vegas/ Neverland May Be Jacko's Ticket to Vegas]. TMZ.com. Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref><ref>[http://ukpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5h88TcEC8zCjFsjTO6G5UKwOV0bOQ Jacko gives up Neverland ranch deed] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215051134/http://ukpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5h88TcEC8zCjFsjTO6G5UKwOV0bOQ |date=December 15, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/04/14/michael-jackson-auction-lifestyle-collecting-michael-jackson.html | work=Forbes | first=Susan | last=Adams | title=Ten Most Expensive Michael Jackson Collectibles | date=2009-04-14 | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120525231159/http://www.forbes.com/2009/04/14/michael-jackson-auction-lifestyle-collecting-michael-jackson.html | archivedate=2012-05-25 | url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Santa Barbara County]] Assessor's Office stated Jackson sold an unknown proportion of his property rights for $35 million.<ref>[http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b68573_michael_jackson_lets_neverland_fly_away.html Michael Jackson Lets Neverland Fly Away]. E! Online (2008-11-12). Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref><ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/people/neverland-peters-out-for-pops-peter-pan/2008/11/13/1226318822205.html People - Entertainment]. smh.com.au (2008-11-13). Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref> Subsequent news reports however, indicated that Colony Capital had invested only $22.5 million in the property.<ref name=\"leitereg1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/realestate/hot-property/la-fi-hotprop-20150531-story.html|title=Former Neverland ranch for sale at $100 million|last=Leitereg|first=Lauren Beale, Neal J.|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> In any event, reliable sources indicate that Colony is the majority owner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4-traders.com/COLONY-CAPITAL-INC-5587701/news/Colony-Capital-Michael-Jackson-s-Neverland-Ranch-back-on-the-market-for-lower-price-23973128/|title=Colony Capital Inc : Colony Capital Inc share news and information {{!}} Nyse: {{!}} 4-Traders|last=4-traders|website=www.4-traders.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/realestate/la-hmw-hotpropjackson7-2009jan07-story.html|title=Michael Jackson leases Bel-Air mansion for $100,000 a month|last=Brenoff|first=By Ann|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref name=\"carlyle1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erincarlyle/2015/05/29/sale-of-michael-jacksons-100-million-neverland-ranch-would-be-win-for-colony-capital/#399c2bc91c8a|title=Sale Of Michael Jackson's $100 Million Neverland Ranch Would Be Win For Colony Capital|last=Carlyle|first=Erin|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nKyle Forsyth, Colony's project manager, described the estate's Tudor-style buildings and savanna-like grasslands as \"English country manor meets Kenya.\" Eventually, Colony hopes to sell the ranch, located in Santa Barbara County, in its entirety. Subdividing it, says Forsyth, \"would destroy it.\"<ref>smith, Ethan. (2009-06-13) [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124484259109711019 Economic Reality Prompts a Makeover at 'Neverland' - WSJ.com]. Online.wsj.com. Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref>\n\nSince 2009, the Neverland Ranch rides Balloon Samba, Jeeps, Wave Swinger and Dinos have been featured attractions at the [[California State Fair]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]].<ref>[http://apps.calexpo.com/fair/PressRelease/ViewPressRelease.asp?PRelId=407 California State Fair 2009 Press Release]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100112203352/http://apps.calexpo.com/fair/PressRelease/ViewPressRelease.asp?PRelId=407 |date=January 12, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Death of Michael Jackson==\n{{Main|Death of Michael Jackson}}\n\n[[Image:Neverland-ranch-memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Fans visiting the makeshift memorial set up outside the Neverland Ranch entrance shortly after Jackson's death.]]\n\nFollowing [[Death of Michael Jackson|Jackson's death]], press reports during June 28\u201329, 2009, claimed that his family intended to bury him at the Neverland Ranch, eventually turning it into a place of [[pilgrimage]] for his fans, similar to how [[Graceland]] has become a destination for fans of [[Elvis Presley]].<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/06/28/jackson-wanted-to-be-buried-at-neverland-mansion-115875-21476865/ Michael Jackson wanted to be buried at Neverland mansion] The ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' June 28, 2008</ref> The singer's father [[Joseph Jackson (manager)|Joseph Jackson]] later denied the reports.<ref>[https://www.nme.com/news/michael-jackson/45739 Michael Jackson will not be buried at Neverland Ranch ] ''[[New Musical Express]]'' 29 June 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1614944/20090629/jackson_michael.jhtml Michael Jackson's Family Still Considering Funeral Plans] ''[[MTV]]'' website June 29, 2009</ref> Construction equipment and gardeners entered the grounds on July 1, prompting speculation that preparations were being made for something related to Jackson's death, but local officials stated that a burial there would be only allowed if the owners of the ranch would go through a permitting process with county and state government before establishing a cemetery at the site. Jackson's 2002 will gives his entire estate to a family trust.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jackson family says the singer's will has surfaced |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090630/ap_en_mu/us_michael_jackson |accessdate=27 May 2015 |location=Los Angeles |work=Yahoo News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 30, 2009 |ref=Web Archive: Jackson family says the singer's will has surfaced |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703120730/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090630/ap_en_mu/us_michael_jackson |archivedate=July 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe ranch was the setting for two media appearances on July 2, 2009. [[Jermaine Jackson]] took ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'''s [[Matt Lauer]] on a tour of the main house,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.today.com/news/jermaine-jackson-i-wish-it-was-me-1C9013427 | title=Jermaine Jackson: 'I wish it was me' | date=2 July 2009 | accessdate=15 December 2017 | author=Celizic, Mike}}</ref> and he was interviewed on the grounds of the house by [[Larry King]] for [[Larry King Live|his show]].\n\nIn January 2013, singer [[Lady Gaga]] announced her willingness to help Jackson's children in keeping the ranch by investing in the property.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/lady-gaga/68199 | location =London | work=NME | title=Lady Gaga wants to restore Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch | date=2013-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Restoration==\n[[File:NeverlandRidesGone.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Neverland Ranch after the carnival rides were removed.]]\nThe amusement rides and animals were gone by 2009,<ref name=\"leitereg1\"/> replaced with a [[meditation|meditative]] [[zen garden]] and a section decorated with [[Peter Pan]], Michael Jackson's favorite fictional hero.\n\nIn May 2015, it was announced that the Neverland Ranch, renamed Sycamore Valley Ranch, would be put up for sale with an initial price tag of $100 million. By that time, Colony NorthStar had completed extensive renovations to the property.<ref name=\"carlyle1\"/> Many people, including fans, protested and disagreed with the decision. Jermaine Jackson, elder brother of Michael wrote an open letter to Colony NorthStar expressing his disagreement with their decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-jacksons-onetime-neverland-lists-for-100-million-1432838117|website=Wall Street Journal|title=Michael Jackson's Onetime Neverland Lists for $100 Million|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\n\nAs of May 2016, the 2,698 acre ranch, jointly owned by the Jackson estate and Colony NorthStar,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/troymcmullen/2017/03/01/a-33-million-price-cut-for-michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch/#5b2b1e0e18e6|title=A $33 Million Price Cut for Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch|last=McMullen|first=Troy|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> was being sold by [[Sotheby's International Realty]] with an asking price of $100 million.<ref name=\"sothebysrealty.com\">{{cite web|title=5225 Figueroa Mountain Road, Los Olivos,California,93441 United States|url=http://www.sothebysrealty.com/eng/sales/detail/180-l-1173-zqltps/sycamore-valley-ranch-los-olivos-ca-93441|website=sothebysrealty.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412204310/http://www.sothebysrealty.com/eng/sales/detail/180-l-1173-zqltps/sycamore-valley-ranch-los-olivos-ca-93441|archivedate= April 12, 2016|accessdate= December 6, 2017}}</ref> The price included the 12,598 square foot six bedroom Normandy-style mansion, the four-acre lake with waterfall, a pool house, three guest houses, a tennis court, and a 5,500-square-foot movie theater and stage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-25/why-michael-jackson-s-neverland-ranch-still-isn-t-sold|title=Why Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Still Isn't Sold|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.instyle.com/lifestyle/home-decorating/home-tours/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-listed-for-sale|title=Michael Jackson's Famed Neverland Ranch Listed for $67 Million|work=InStyle.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> The train station and railway tracks were also included. According to [[TIME]], the owners were \"specifically looking for a buyer who doesn\u2019t plan to turn the place into a museum for the singer\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3900501/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch/|title=You Can Buy Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.coldwellbankerluxury.com/inside-sycamore-valley-ranch-neverland-ranch/|title=Inside Sycamore Valley Ranch, Formerly Known as Neverland Ranch - Coldwell Banker Global Luxury Blog - Luxury Home & Style|date=2017-05-02|work=Coldwell Banker Global Luxury Blog - Luxury Home & Style|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDue to lack of interest, the asking price of the ranch had fallen to $67 million by February 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2017/03/02/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-back-on-market-for-67m/98625540/|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch back on market for $67M|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-03-02|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.instyle.com/lifestyle/home-decorating/home-tours/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-listed-for-sale#2706838|title=Michael Jackson's Famed Neverland Ranch Listed for $67 Million|work=InStyle.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> The property was still on the market in early 2018, at the same price, with [[Coldwell Banker]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.joycerey.com/beverly-hills-properties/sycamore-valley-ranch-formerly-known-as-neverland-ranch-luxury-real-estate/|title=Sycamore Valley Ranch Formerly Neverland Ranch {{!}} Joyce Rey|work=Joyce Rey|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629235843/http://www.joycerey.com/beverly-hills-properties/sycamore-valley-ranch-formerly-known-as-neverland-ranch-luxury-real-estate/|archive-date=2018-06-29|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/photo-galleries/on-the-grounds-of-michael-jackson-s-100m-neverland-ranch-1.2787730|title=On the grounds of Michael Jackson's $100M 'Neverland Ranch'|work=CTVNews|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the asking price of the ranch was reduced to $31 million, $69 million less than the original asking price of $100 million in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/28/entertainment/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-sale/index.html|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch is back on the market at a reduced price, report says |last1=Respers France|first1=Lisa|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=February 28, 2019|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> The listing agent for the ranch says nothing has changed except the price. The ranch's structures and landscaping are still being maintained.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neverland No Longer, Michael Jackson's Ranch Gets Massive $69M Price Cut |url=https://www.realtor.com/news/celebrity-real-estate/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-huge-discount/ |website=realtor.com |publisher=realtor.com |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n= Aeryn =\nWelcome biotch! You figured it out. You're probably wondering how this is possible, don't ask it's probably illegal. So be proud, until this gets taken down, you're on Neverland's wikipedia! You've made history bbg. Tomorrow you'll get your fourth clue, so in the meantime read this article we wrote for you.\n\n\nAeryn Reed is known as Micheal Jackson's biggest fan. Although she never had the opportunity to meet him, it is said that if he could come back to life, he would go visit her. The girl in question is an amazing, wonderful, funny, and beautiful young woman who knows every Micheal Jackson song by heart. If you ask me, she deserves more than anything to receive the estate and would make it three times more beautiful than it already is. Never doubt her capacities because she will blow you away with her knowledge and amazingness. So please Wiki, don't take this down, and let the world know who this amazing birthday girl is.\n<br />\n==See also==\n*[[Michael Jackson]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Neverland Ranch}}\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Figueroa+mountain+rd.&ll=34.746430,-120.087111&sll=34.652771,-120.104432&spn=0.008014,0.011727&sspn=0.022797,0.043228&t=k&hl=en Satellite Images of Neverland]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080415144307/http://www.terrastories.com/bearings/inside-neverland-ranch Night images of Neverland Ranch]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/search/show/?q=jackson+-falls&w=29219917%40N05&ss=2&ct=0&mt=all&adv=1 Aerial photos of Neverland, before and after removal of rides]\n* [http://www.thepinnaclelist.com/blog/directory/neverland-valley-ranch-5225-figueroa-mountain-road-los-olivos-ca/ The Pinnacle List - Showcase of Neverland]\n* [http://www.michaeljackson.com/ Website Michael Jackson]\n{{Defunct Amusement Parks in California}}\n{{Michael Jackson}}\n{{Santa Ynez River}}\n\n[[Category:1988 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2 ft gauge railways in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1982]]\n[[Category:Houses in Santa Barbara County, California]]\n[[Category:Michael Jackson]]\n[[Category:Michael Jackson sexual abuse allegations]]\n[[Category:Ranches in California]]\n[[Category:Santa Ynez Valley]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Personal home of Michael Jackson}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Neverland Valley Ranch \n| image = NeverlandRides.jpg\n| caption = Neverland Ranch amusement rides pictured in August 2008\n| location = 5225 Figueroa Mountain Road, [[Los Olivos, California|Los Olivos]]\n| location2 = [[California]]\n| location3 = United States\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.74107|-120.09158|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-CA|display=title,inline}}\n| status = closed\n| owner = Estate of [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Colony Capital]]\n| area = {{convert|2700|acre}}\n| homepage = www.sycamorevalley.com\n}}\n\n[[File:Neverland Ranch's gates.jpg|thumb|right|Neverland Ranch gates]]\n'''Sycamore Valley Ranch'''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Characterization of pathway engineered strains of filamentous fungi in submerged cultures|last=Poulsen, B. R.|isbn=9085041546|oclc=1016620715}}</ref>  (formerly and most famously '''Neverland Ranch''',<ref name=\"NNM\">[http://www.edhat.com/site/tidbit.cfm?id=2752 \"Neverland Never More\"], by William Etling (author of ''Sideways in Neverland: Life in the Santa Ynez Valley''), EdHat.com, 2009.</ref> or simply '''Neverland''') is a developed property in [[Santa Barbara County, California]], located at 5225 Figueroa Mountain Road, [[Los Olivos, California]], on the edge of [[Los Padres National Forest]]. It is known for being the home and private [[amusement park]] of American entertainer [[Michael Jackson]] from 1988 until 2005.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6128664/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-frozen-in-time|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Frozen in Time|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2014-06-20|accessdate=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref name=\"Petersen\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Ellis-Petersen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/aug/01/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-sell-50-million|title=Michael Jackson Neverland Ranch expected to fetch up to $85m|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=2014-08-01|accessdate=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sophie Smith|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/abroad/michael-jacksonsneverland-ranch-returns-market-amid-documentary/|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch returns to the market amid documentary controversy|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=March 4, 2019|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOriginally named '''Zaca Laderas Ranch''', the estate was renamed to Sycamore Valley Ranch shortly after it was purchased by property developer William Bone in 1981.<ref name=\"Time\"/> In 1988, the ranch was sold to Jackson, who renamed it after [[Neverland]], the fantasy island in the story of [[Peter Pan]], a boy who never grows up.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"Petersen\"/> Jackson's first encounter with the ranch came when he visited [[Paul McCartney]], who was staying there during their filming of the \"[[Say Say Say]]\" video in 1983. According to [[La Toya Jackson]], Michael expressed interest to her in someday owning the property at that time.<ref>{{cite book|author1=La Toya Jackson|author2=Jeffr\u00e9 Phillips|title=Starting Over|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SeQfvRHvZfwC&pg=PA69|year=2012|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2059-7|page=69}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, the ranch is owned by [[Colony Capital]] and has been for sale for several years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erincarlyle/2015/05/29/sale-of-michael-jacksons-100-million-neverland-ranch-would-be-win-for-colony-capital/#75f257361c8a|title=Sale Of Michael Jackson's $100 Million Neverland Ranch Would Be Win For Colony Capital|last=Carlyle |first=Erin|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> The ranch is located about 5 miles (8&nbsp;km) north of unincorporated Los Olivos, and about eight miles (13&nbsp;km) north of the town of [[Santa Ynez, California|Santa Ynez]]. The Chamberlin Ranch is to the west, and the rugged La Laguna Ranch, is to the north. The Santa Barbara County Assessor's office says the ranch is approximately 2,700 acres (1100 hectares).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4792028.stm | title=Dispute shuts down Jackson ranch | work=[[BBC News]] | date=2006-03-10 | accessdate=2007-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nThe estate was originally known as the '''Zaca Laderas Ranch''' at the time of its purchase by the property developer William Bone in 1981.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Bone renamed the estate the '''Sycamore Valley Ranch''' and moved there with his family. Bone commissioned the architect Robert Altevers to design the principal buildings on the ranch, and the pair spent two and a half years researching potential designs and ideas. The 13,000 square foot (1,200 m\u00b2) main house was completed in 1982, based on a design by Altevers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/01/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-relisted--with-a-big-price-cut.html|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch relisted \u2013 with a big price cut|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> with formal gardens, a stone bridge, and a four-acre lake with a five-foot waterfall. Bone later said that in building the house he had \"...a desire to express everything I had learned in 15 years of home building...I achieved here all the things I wanted to do in my business but could not\".<ref name=AD09>{{cite news|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/neverland-ranch-article|title=Neverland|date=October 31, 2009|work=[[Architectural Digest]]|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> He had considered converting the property to a country club but did not do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/la-me-jacksontimeline-neverland-story.html|title=Hot Property: Michael Jackson to Be Home on the Range|last=Ryon|first=Ruth|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n\n==Residence of Michael Jackson==\n[[File:Aerial-NeverlandTrainStation.jpg|thumb|Neverland's train station, Katherine Station, with [[floral clock]]<ref>https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/neverland-ranch-michael-jackson-article</ref>]]\n\nJackson purchased the estate from Bone in 1988<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news |title=At Neverland, they believe |work=USA Today |first=Cesar G |last=Soriano |date=2003-11-24 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/2003-11-23-neverland-believe_x.htm }}</ref> for an unknown amount: some sources indicate $19.5 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-for-sale-20150528-story.html|title=Neverland Ranch, former home of Michael Jackson, on the market for $100M|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/troymcmullen/2017/03/01/a-33-million-price-cut-for-michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch/#141c22ba18e6|title=A $33 Million Price Cut for Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch|last=McMullen|first=Troy|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> while others suggest it was closer to $30 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1988-03-20/realestate/re-1930_1_michael-jackson|title=Michael Jackson to Be Home on the Range|last=Ryon|first=Ruth|date=1988-03-20|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Vegas Hosting Big Jackson Family Auction. |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Fox News |date=2007-05-29 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,276076,00.html?sPage=fnc/entertainment/jackson |access-date=2019-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524084833/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,276076,00.html?sPage=fnc%2Fentertainment%2Fjackson |archive-date=2013-05-24 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The property was initially purchased by a [[Trust law|trust]] with Jackson's lawyer, John Branca, and his accountant, Marshall Gelfand, as trustees, for reasons of privacy. The arrangement was later rescinded by Jackson in April 1988 and he became the ultimate owner of the property.<ref name=\"Taraborrelli2010\">{{cite book|author=J. Randy Taraborrelli|title=Michael Jackson: The Magic, the Madness, the Whole Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=99AABNGOHGYC|year=2010|publisher=Pan|isbn=978-0-330-51565-8|page=386}}</ref> It was Jackson's home as well as his private amusement park, with numerous artistic garden statues and a [[petting zoo]].\n\nThe property included three railroads: one {{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]] named \"Neverland Valley Railroad\", with a steam locomotive named ''Katherine'' after his mother ([[Crown Metal Products|Crown]] {{whyte|4-4-0}} (2B), built in 1973), and two coaches. The other was a {{RailGauge|2ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]], with a  [[C. P. Huntington#Working replicas|C. P. Huntington replica locomotive]] made by [[Chance Rides]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steamlocomotive.com/lists/searchdb.php?str=Neverland+Ranch&country=USA|title=Surviving Steam Locomotive Search|work=steamlocomotive.com}}</ref> There was also a custom-made private electric train that was purchased by Jackson for his own children Prince, Paris and Blanket. The train was manufactured in 2001 from a German company [https://www.merkur-kids.de/ Elektro-Mobiltechnik]. The train was set up in the yard at Neverland behind the main house and had 100 feet of track.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-02/michael-jackson-s-neverland-ranch-train-is-coming-to-auction|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Train Is Coming to Auction|date=2019-06-07|access-date=2019-06-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThere was also a [[Ferris wheel]], [[Carousel]], [[Zipper (ride)|Zipper]], [[Octopus (ride)|Octopus]], [[Pirate ship (ride)|Pirate Ship]], [[Wave Swinger]], Super Slide, [[roller coaster]], [[bumper car]]s, and an [[amusement arcade]]. The master closet also contained a secret [[safe room]] for security.\n\nSome of the events that took place at the Ranch included the wedding of [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Larry Fortensky]] in 1991, the live [[Oprah Winfrey]] interview of Jackson in 1993, and an event in 1995 when Jackson and [[Lisa Marie Presley]] hosted children from around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2014/06/22/michael_jacksons_neverland_remains_in_limbo_years_after_his_death.html|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland remains in limbo years after his death {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNeverland Ranch was searched extensively by police officers in connection with the ''[[Trial of Michael Jackson|People v. Jackson]]'' trial after he was charged with multiple counts of [[Sexual abuse|molesting]] a minor in 2003. Jackson was acquitted of all charges. However, Jackson stated he would never live at the property again as he no longer considered the ranch a home and did not return to Neverland.<ref name=\"rollingstone1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-selling-for-67-million-w469968|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Devalued in Real Estate Market|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> Jackson's sister, [[La Toya Jackson|La Toya]], wrote of her experience staying at the ranch during her brother's trial in her 2012 memoir ''Starting Over''.<ref name=\"JacksonPhillips2012\">{{cite book|author1=La Toya Jackson|author2=Jeffr\u00e9 Phillips|title=Starting Over|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SeQfvRHvZfwC|date=29 May 2012|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2059-7|page=297}}</ref> In 2006, the facilities were closed and most of the staff were dismissed, with a spokesperson stating that this was the reflection of the fact that Jackson no longer lived there.\n\nNeverland Ranch has a central role in the allegations against Jackson of [[child sexual abuse]]; it is one of the main sites where Jackson's accusers have said the sexual abuse took place. The ranch's association with sexual abuse allegations was described as a possible reason for a significant decrease in value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/feb/28/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-reduces-price-by-70m|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch cuts sale price by $69m|first=Guardian|last=music|date=28 February 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/neverland-ranch-for-sale-michael-jackson.html</ref>\n\n==Financial status==\nReports of foreclosure proceedings against Neverland Ranch were published on October 22, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tmz.com/2007/11/06/neverland-in-foreclosure/ |date=2007-11-06 |accessdate=2007-11-07 |title=Neverland in Foreclosure? |publisher=TMZ.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ml-implode.com/info/jackson-NOD.pdf |title=Foreclosure Detail Report |accessdate=2007-11-07}}</ref> A spokesperson for Jackson said that the loan was merely being [[refinancing|refinanced]] and Jackson (later his estate) remained the majority stake holder, with a legal retention of 87.5% of the ranch.<ref name=\"scribd.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/101284813/mj-estate-second-accounting|title=MJ Estate Second Accounting|work=scribd.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7088491.stm|date=2007-11-10|accessdate=2007-11-10|title=Jackson 'will not lose Neverland'|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aerial-NeverlandZoo.jpg|thumb|Former zoo buildings, July 2009]]\nOn February 25, 2008, Jackson received word from Financial Title Company, the trustee, that unless he paid off $24,525,906.61 by March 19, a [[public auction]] would go forward of the land, buildings, and other items such as the rides, trains, and art.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/projects/pdf/AR-BC320_20080226_114706.pdf Notice of Trustee's Sale], Santa Barbara County Recorder via Fox News [http://www.sbcvote.com/opis/details.aspx?DocNum=2008-0010131 Record no. 2008-0010131]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, February 25, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Neverland Ranch Set for Auction |agency=Associated Press |work=Forbes |date=2008-02-26 |url=https://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2008/02/26/ap4700673.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080317164555/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2008/02/26/ap4700673.html |archivedate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref> On March 13, 2008, Jackson's lawyer L. Londell McMillan announced that a private agreement had been reached with the private investment group, [[Fortress Investment Group|Fortress Investment]], to save Jackson's ownership of the ranch.<ref name=saves>{{cite news |title=Michael Jackson 'saves Neverland' |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7295101.stm |date=2008-03-13 |accessdate=2008-03-13 }}</ref> Before the agreement, Jackson owed three months' [[arrears]] on the property.<ref name=saves/> McMillan did not reveal the details of the deal.\n\nOn May 12, 2008, a [[foreclosure]] [[auction]] for the ranch was canceled after [[Colony Capital]], an investment company run by billionaire Tom Barrack, purchased the [[loan]], which was in default. The selling price was $22.5 million.<ref name=\"rollingstone1\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Foreclosure auction on Jackson's Neverland Ranch is canceled |agency=Associated Press |publisher=CNN |date=2008-05-13 |accessdate=2008-05-13 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/12/jackson.neverland.ap/index.html |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080514020618/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/12/jackson.neverland.ap/index.html |archivedate = May 14, 2008}}</ref> In a press release, Jackson stated, \"I am pleased with recent developments involving Neverland Ranch and I am in discussions with Colony and [[Tom Barrack]] with regard to the Ranch and other matters that would allow me to focus on the future.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Neverland Ranch Note Sold to Colony Capital |publisher=Business Wire |date=2008-05-11 |accessdate=2008-05-13 |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080511005036/en }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5hZNgbrgnco68wdSY5q0bFdgp2MYgD90KF3F80 |title=Neverland Ranch foreclosure auction canceled |agency=Associated Press |date=2008-05-12 |accessdate=2008-05-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518174244/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5hZNgbrgnco68wdSY5q0bFdgp2MYgD90KF3F80 |archivedate=May 18, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 10, 2008, Jackson transferred the title to Sycamore Valley Ranch Company, LLC, and neighbors reported immediate activity on the property, including the amusement rides being trucked along the highway.<ref name=NNM/> Jackson still owned an unknown stake in the property, since Sycamore Valley Ranch was a [[joint venture]] between Jackson (represented by McMillan) and an affiliate of Colony Capital.<ref>[http://www.taletela.com/news/775/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-is-sold Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Is Sold] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727103118/http://www.taletela.com/news/775/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-is-sold |date=2009-07-27 }}. TaleTela. Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref><ref>[https://www.tmz.com/2008/11/12/neverland-may-be-jackos-ticket-to-vegas/ Neverland May Be Jacko's Ticket to Vegas]. TMZ.com. Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref><ref>[http://ukpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5h88TcEC8zCjFsjTO6G5UKwOV0bOQ Jacko gives up Neverland ranch deed] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215051134/http://ukpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5h88TcEC8zCjFsjTO6G5UKwOV0bOQ |date=December 15, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/04/14/michael-jackson-auction-lifestyle-collecting-michael-jackson.html | work=Forbes | first=Susan | last=Adams | title=Ten Most Expensive Michael Jackson Collectibles | date=2009-04-14 | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120525231159/http://www.forbes.com/2009/04/14/michael-jackson-auction-lifestyle-collecting-michael-jackson.html | archivedate=2012-05-25 | url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Santa Barbara County]] Assessor's Office stated Jackson sold an unknown proportion of his property rights for $35 million.<ref>[http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b68573_michael_jackson_lets_neverland_fly_away.html Michael Jackson Lets Neverland Fly Away]. E! Online (2008-11-12). Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref><ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/people/neverland-peters-out-for-pops-peter-pan/2008/11/13/1226318822205.html People - Entertainment]. smh.com.au (2008-11-13). Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref> Subsequent news reports however, indicated that Colony Capital had invested only $22.5 million in the property.<ref name=\"leitereg1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/realestate/hot-property/la-fi-hotprop-20150531-story.html|title=Former Neverland ranch for sale at $100 million|last=Leitereg|first=Lauren Beale, Neal J.|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> In any event, reliable sources indicate that Colony is the majority owner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4-traders.com/COLONY-CAPITAL-INC-5587701/news/Colony-Capital-Michael-Jackson-s-Neverland-Ranch-back-on-the-market-for-lower-price-23973128/|title=Colony Capital Inc : Colony Capital Inc share news and information {{!}} Nyse: {{!}} 4-Traders|last=4-traders|website=www.4-traders.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/realestate/la-hmw-hotpropjackson7-2009jan07-story.html|title=Michael Jackson leases Bel-Air mansion for $100,000 a month|last=Brenoff|first=By Ann|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref name=\"carlyle1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erincarlyle/2015/05/29/sale-of-michael-jacksons-100-million-neverland-ranch-would-be-win-for-colony-capital/#399c2bc91c8a|title=Sale Of Michael Jackson's $100 Million Neverland Ranch Would Be Win For Colony Capital|last=Carlyle|first=Erin|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nKyle Forsyth, Colony's project manager, described the estate's Tudor-style buildings and savanna-like grasslands as \"English country manor meets Kenya.\" Eventually, Colony hopes to sell the ranch, located in Santa Barbara County, in its entirety. Subdividing it, says Forsyth, \"would destroy it.\"<ref>smith, Ethan. (2009-06-13) [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124484259109711019 Economic Reality Prompts a Makeover at 'Neverland' - WSJ.com]. Online.wsj.com. Retrieved on 2011-05-18.</ref>\n\nSince 2009, the Neverland Ranch rides Balloon Samba, Jeeps, Wave Swinger and Dinos have been featured attractions at the [[California State Fair]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]].<ref>[http://apps.calexpo.com/fair/PressRelease/ViewPressRelease.asp?PRelId=407 California State Fair 2009 Press Release]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100112203352/http://apps.calexpo.com/fair/PressRelease/ViewPressRelease.asp?PRelId=407 |date=January 12, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Death of Michael Jackson==\n{{Main|Death of Michael Jackson}}\n\n[[Image:Neverland-ranch-memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Fans visiting the makeshift memorial set up outside the Neverland Ranch entrance shortly after Jackson's death.]]\n\nFollowing [[Death of Michael Jackson|Jackson's death]], press reports during June 28\u201329, 2009, claimed that his family intended to bury him at the Neverland Ranch, eventually turning it into a place of [[pilgrimage]] for his fans, similar to how [[Graceland]] has become a destination for fans of [[Elvis Presley]].<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/06/28/jackson-wanted-to-be-buried-at-neverland-mansion-115875-21476865/ Michael Jackson wanted to be buried at Neverland mansion] The ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' June 28, 2008</ref> The singer's father [[Joseph Jackson (manager)|Joseph Jackson]] later denied the reports.<ref>[https://www.nme.com/news/michael-jackson/45739 Michael Jackson will not be buried at Neverland Ranch ] ''[[New Musical Express]]'' 29 June 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1614944/20090629/jackson_michael.jhtml Michael Jackson's Family Still Considering Funeral Plans] ''[[MTV]]'' website June 29, 2009</ref> Construction equipment and gardeners entered the grounds on July 1, prompting speculation that preparations were being made for something related to Jackson's death, but local officials stated that a burial there would be only allowed if the owners of the ranch would go through a permitting process with county and state government before establishing a cemetery at the site. Jackson's 2002 will gives his entire estate to a family trust.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jackson family says the singer's will has surfaced |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090630/ap_en_mu/us_michael_jackson |accessdate=27 May 2015 |location=Los Angeles |work=Yahoo News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 30, 2009 |ref=Web Archive: Jackson family says the singer's will has surfaced |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703120730/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090630/ap_en_mu/us_michael_jackson |archivedate=July 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe ranch was the setting for two media appearances on July 2, 2009. [[Jermaine Jackson]] took ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'''s [[Matt Lauer]] on a tour of the main house,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.today.com/news/jermaine-jackson-i-wish-it-was-me-1C9013427 | title=Jermaine Jackson: 'I wish it was me' | date=2 July 2009 | accessdate=15 December 2017 | author=Celizic, Mike}}</ref> and he was interviewed on the grounds of the house by [[Larry King]] for [[Larry King Live|his show]].\n\nIn January 2013, singer [[Lady Gaga]] announced her willingness to help Jackson's children in keeping the ranch by investing in the property.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/lady-gaga/68199 | location =London | work=NME | title=Lady Gaga wants to restore Michael Jackson's Neverland ranch | date=2013-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Restoration==\n[[File:NeverlandRidesGone.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Neverland Ranch after the carnival rides were removed.]]\nThe amusement rides and animals were gone by 2009,<ref name=\"leitereg1\"/> replaced with a [[meditation|meditative]] [[zen garden]] and a section decorated with [[Peter Pan]], Michael Jackson's favorite fictional hero.\n\nIn May 2015, it was announced that the Neverland Ranch, renamed Sycamore Valley Ranch, would be put up for sale with an initial price tag of $100 million. By that time, Colony NorthStar had completed extensive renovations to the property.<ref name=\"carlyle1\"/> Many people, including fans, protested and disagreed with the decision. Jermaine Jackson, elder brother of Michael wrote an open letter to Colony NorthStar expressing his disagreement with their decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-jacksons-onetime-neverland-lists-for-100-million-1432838117|website=Wall Street Journal|title=Michael Jackson's Onetime Neverland Lists for $100 Million|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\n\nAs of May 2016, the 2,698 acre ranch, jointly owned by the Jackson estate and Colony NorthStar,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/troymcmullen/2017/03/01/a-33-million-price-cut-for-michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch/#5b2b1e0e18e6|title=A $33 Million Price Cut for Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch|last=McMullen|first=Troy|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> was being sold by [[Sotheby's International Realty]] with an asking price of $100 million.<ref name=\"sothebysrealty.com\">{{cite web|title=5225 Figueroa Mountain Road, Los Olivos,California,93441 United States|url=http://www.sothebysrealty.com/eng/sales/detail/180-l-1173-zqltps/sycamore-valley-ranch-los-olivos-ca-93441|website=sothebysrealty.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412204310/http://www.sothebysrealty.com/eng/sales/detail/180-l-1173-zqltps/sycamore-valley-ranch-los-olivos-ca-93441|archivedate= April 12, 2016|accessdate= December 6, 2017}}</ref> The price included the 12,598 square foot six bedroom Normandy-style mansion, the four-acre lake with waterfall, a pool house, three guest houses, a tennis court, and a 5,500-square-foot movie theater and stage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-25/why-michael-jackson-s-neverland-ranch-still-isn-t-sold|title=Why Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch Still Isn't Sold|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.instyle.com/lifestyle/home-decorating/home-tours/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-listed-for-sale|title=Michael Jackson's Famed Neverland Ranch Listed for $67 Million|work=InStyle.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> The train station and railway tracks were also included. According to [[TIME]], the owners were \"specifically looking for a buyer who doesn\u2019t plan to turn the place into a museum for the singer\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3900501/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch/|title=You Can Buy Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.coldwellbankerluxury.com/inside-sycamore-valley-ranch-neverland-ranch/|title=Inside Sycamore Valley Ranch, Formerly Known as Neverland Ranch - Coldwell Banker Global Luxury Blog - Luxury Home & Style|date=2017-05-02|work=Coldwell Banker Global Luxury Blog - Luxury Home & Style|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDue to lack of interest, the asking price of the ranch had fallen to $67 million by February 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2017/03/02/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-back-on-market-for-67m/98625540/|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch back on market for $67M|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-03-02|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.instyle.com/lifestyle/home-decorating/home-tours/michael-jacksons-neverland-ranch-listed-for-sale#2706838|title=Michael Jackson's Famed Neverland Ranch Listed for $67 Million|work=InStyle.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> The property was still on the market in early 2018, at the same price, with [[Coldwell Banker]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.joycerey.com/beverly-hills-properties/sycamore-valley-ranch-formerly-known-as-neverland-ranch-luxury-real-estate/|title=Sycamore Valley Ranch Formerly Neverland Ranch {{!}} Joyce Rey|work=Joyce Rey|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629235843/http://www.joycerey.com/beverly-hills-properties/sycamore-valley-ranch-formerly-known-as-neverland-ranch-luxury-real-estate/|archive-date=2018-06-29|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/photo-galleries/on-the-grounds-of-michael-jackson-s-100m-neverland-ranch-1.2787730|title=On the grounds of Michael Jackson's $100M 'Neverland Ranch'|work=CTVNews|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the asking price of the ranch was reduced to $31 million, $69 million less than the original asking price of $100 million in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/28/entertainment/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-sale/index.html|title=Michael Jackson's Neverland Ranch is back on the market at a reduced price, report says |last1=Respers France|first1=Lisa|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=February 28, 2019|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> The listing agent for the ranch says nothing has changed except the price. The ranch's structures and landscaping are still being maintained.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neverland No Longer, Michael Jackson's Ranch Gets Massive $69M Price Cut |url=https://www.realtor.com/news/celebrity-real-estate/michael-jackson-neverland-ranch-huge-discount/ |website=realtor.com |publisher=realtor.com |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Michael Jackson]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Neverland Ranch}}\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Figueroa+mountain+rd.&ll=34.746430,-120.087111&sll=34.652771,-120.104432&spn=0.008014,0.011727&sspn=0.022797,0.043228&t=k&hl=en Satellite Images of Neverland]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080415144307/http://www.terrastories.com/bearings/inside-neverland-ranch Night images of Neverland Ranch]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/search/show/?q=jackson+-falls&w=29219917%40N05&ss=2&ct=0&mt=all&adv=1 Aerial photos of Neverland, before and after removal of rides]\n* [http://www.thepinnaclelist.com/blog/directory/neverland-valley-ranch-5225-figueroa-mountain-road-los-olivos-ca/ The Pinnacle List - Showcase of Neverland]\n* [http://www.michaeljackson.com/ Website Michael Jackson]\n{{Defunct Amusement Parks in California}}\n{{Michael Jackson}}\n{{Santa Ynez River}}\n\n[[Category:1988 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2 ft gauge railways in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1982]]\n[[Category:Houses in Santa Barbara County, California]]\n[[Category:Michael Jackson]]\n[[Category:Michael Jackson sexual abuse allegations]]\n[[Category:Ranches in California]]\n[[Category:Santa Ynez Valley]]\n", "name_user": "Yentelperson", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neverland_Ranch"}
